<title>The |u&apos; ||ke&apos; or Tshaka</title>
<summary>The |u&apos; ||ke&apos;. or Tshaka, is a small plant and is used as part of the purification ritual, or |koa. It intoxicates and can kill people if handled incorrectly (at the wrong time of day), and is thus feared. The ≠nabbi does not kill people and is given when the people &apos;seek their hearts&apos;. Both plants seem to be effective at specific times of day.</summary><comments>1) p.9921v: !nanni heard this from his paternal grandfather (Karu), 2) p.9923v: the ≠nabbi is given to people to eat &apos;when we seek our heart&apos;, 3) See also <i>|u&apos; ||ke&apos; in food</i>, 4) This story is found in Book XI &amp; XII-11</comments><date>25 August 1881 (started)</date><storypages>9922-9924</storypages><category>Plants and animals</category><category>Custom and daily life</category><author>!nanni (XI)</author><keyword><kw>|u&apos; ||ke&apos;</kw><subkw>or Tshaka</subkw></keyword>
